🧪 Important Challenge: Create a Failure

Temporarily change:

if [ -f "app/app.sh" ]; then

to:

if [ -f "app/missing.sh" ]; then

Commit and push:

git add .
git commit -m "Test CI failure"
git push

Your GitHub Actions pipeline should fail.

Then fix the problem and push again.

This is an important DevOps skill: understanding how to troubleshoot failed CI pipelines.

🔐 Task 6 – Environment Variables

Update your workflow:

env:
  ENVIRONMENT: production
  APPLICATION_NAME: devops-demo

Example:

name: DevOps CI Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

env:
  ENVIRONMENT: production
  APPLICATION_NAME: devops-demo

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Display Environment
        run: |
          echo "Environment: $ENVIRONMENT"
          echo "Application: $APPLICATION_NAME"
🔒 Task 7 – GitHub Secrets

Never write passwords or tokens directly in your workflow.

Bad:

PASSWORD: mypassword123

Instead, create a GitHub Secret:

Repository
   ↓
Settings
   ↓Secrets and variables
   ↓
Actions
   ↓
New repository secret

Example secret name:

APP_SECRET

Use it:

- name: Use Secret
  run: |
    echo "Secret is configured"
  env:
    APP_SECRET: ${{ secrets.APP_SECRET }}

⚠️ Never print secrets in logs.

📦 Task 8 – Upload Build Artifacts

Add:

- name: Create Build File
  run: |
    mkdir -p build
    echo "Build completed successfully" > build/result.txt

- name: Upload Artifact
  uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
  with:
    name: build-output
    path: build/

After the workflow completes, you can download the build artifact from the Actions run.

